Hi.

00:01:07.049 --> 00:01:08.189
I'm Surma.

00:01:08.189 --> 00:01:09.750
I'm an engineer at
Google in London,

00:01:09.750 --> 00:01:11.909
and I work with the Chrome team.

00:01:11.909 --> 00:01:13.859
In this course, we are
going to understand

00:01:13.859 --> 00:01:17.370
what the web actually is, how
we can use it to your advantage,

00:01:17.370 --> 00:01:20.130
and how you can avoid mistakes
that will make both your user

00:01:20.129 --> 00:01:23.219
experience and security suffer.

00:01:23.219 --> 00:01:26.789
Some of this may seem like
[INAUDIBLE] to you, and it is,

00:01:26.790 --> 00:01:30.132
but we will also go into the
lesser known parts of HTTP.

00:01:30.132 --> 00:01:31.590
To think like an
engineer, you need

00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:34.770
to understand both the
semantics that HTTP uses,

00:01:34.769 --> 00:01:38.219
as well as the implementation
inside the browser.

00:01:38.219 --> 00:01:41.189
We'll use that knowledge to
use browser APIs to the fullest

00:01:41.189 --> 00:01:44.700
potential, secure HTTP
against eavesdroppers,

00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:48.390
and deploy the web's
newest protocol, HTTP2.

00:01:48.390 --> 00:01:51.060
All this knowledge will help
you make informed decisions

00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:54.540
for your app and persuade others
when optimizing and securing

00:01:54.540 --> 00:01:56.609
their apps.

